        "title": "JET: English-Lecture-II ",
        "excerpt":"Number &amp; Letter Series       QUIZ                          Easy      Medium      Hard                                                                                   Next            Number series questions involve identifying the hidden pattern governing the progression of numbers. Common patterns include: 1. Difference-Based Patterns   Consecutive differences:Example:$-1, 5, 15, 29, ?$Differences ‚Üí $6, 10, 14, ‚Ä¶$Pattern: +4 each step.Next difference = $18$ ‚Üí Next term = $29 + 18 = 47$2. Multiplicative Patterns Numbers progress by multiplication or a mix of √ó and ¬± operations:Example:$2, 6, 18, 54, ‚Ä¶$Multiply √ó3 each time. 3. Square, Cube &amp; Polynomial Patterns Some series follow:   $n^2$ or $n^3$  Alternating squares  Quadratic patternsExample:$1, 4, 9, 16, 25‚Ä¶$ ‚Üí perfect squares. 4. Alternating Patterns Two or more sequences interwoven:Example:$5, 7, 12, 14, 19, 21‚Ä¶$ Odd terms: +7 each timeEven terms: +7 each time 5. Mix of Operations Example:$3, 7, 15, 31‚Ä¶$Pattern: √ó2 + 1 Letter Series: Core Concepts Letter series questions follow letter-position logic based on the English alphabet: A = 1, B = 2, C = 3 ‚Ä¶ Z = 26 1. Alphabetic Position Shifts Example:ABD, DGK, HMS, MTB, SBL, ? Break each group:       First letters: A ‚Üí D ‚Üí H ‚Üí M ‚Üí S ‚Üí ?Positions: 1,4,8,13,19 ‚Üí increments +3,+4,+5,+6 ‚Üí next +7 ‚Üí 26 = Z         Second letters: B ‚Üí G ‚Üí M ‚Üí T ‚Üí B ‚Üí ?Positions: 2,7,13,20,2 ‚Üí increments +5,+6,+7,+8 ‚Üí next +9 ‚Üí 2+9=11=K         Third letters: D ‚Üí K ‚Üí S ‚Üí B ‚Üí L ‚Üí ?Positions: 4,11,19,2,12 ‚Üí increments +7,+8,+9,+10 ‚Üí next +1112+11=23=W   So answer = ZKW This pattern‚Äîa fixed incremental jump for each position‚Äîis common. Coding-Decoding Letter Series Coding questions modify letters using a rule. The rule may involve: 1. Forward or Backward Shifts Example:A ‚Üí C (shift +2) 2. Mirroring Against Alphabet Example:A ‚Üî Z, B ‚Üî Y, C ‚Üî X 3. Alternating Shifts Example:+2, ‚àí1, +3, ‚àí2,‚Ä¶ 4. Pattern Seen in Example from Image ‚ÄúIf VARANASI is coded as WCUESGZQ‚Äù Steps typically used:   Each letter shifted differently  Pattern repeats  Could be:          +2, ‚àí4, +6, ‚àí8, ‚Ä¶      Or positions reversed      Or vowel-consonant-based coding      To decode ‚ÄúKOLKATA‚Äù, apply same rule letter-by-letter. How to Approach These Questions Quickly 1. Write Alphabet Positions Always convert letters:K = 11, O = 15, L = 12, A = 1, etc. 2. Check Differences For number series ‚Üí write +, ‚àí, √ó, / differences. 3. Look for Consistency Patterns rarely change mid-series. 4. Check for Alternation If numbers behave strangely ‚Üí check odd &amp; even positions separately. 5. For Coding Map original ‚Üí coded letters and compute exact shifts. Solved Examples (A) Number Series $-1, 5, 15, 29, ?$Differences: $+6, +10, +14, ‚Ä¶$Increase = +4Next diff = 18Answer ‚Üí 29 + 18 = 47 (B) Letter Series ABD, DGK, HMS, MTB, SBL, ?Answer ‚Üí ZKW (C) Coding-Decoding If VARANASI ‚Üí WCUESGZQApply same shifts to KOLKATA.(Final answer depends on detailed rule ‚Üí taught above.) ","categories": ["English"],
